Wow, can you believe it's April already? Happy #LimbDifferenceAwareness month, everyone! In the past, we have been slow to share about this, but as Evie grows, I can see the importance of awareness, and our knowledge has grown as well. This month is incredibly important to our family because it is something that we get the joy of navigating and learning with Evie. It's not always easy, and it can feel lonely at times, which is also why we wanted to share. We believe that with awareness and understanding, we can create a more inclusive world. Our hope is that by sharing, we can help people understand that having a limb difference doesn't define anyone. It's just one aspect of who they are, and it makes their life unique and beautiful. So, let's celebrate differences and add a little extra spice to this already beautiful life!🧡🧡

Before Evie, I had absolutely no idea what went into a prostethic. I, maybe in the back of my mind, thought you showed up, picked one you liked, and left. 
.
That's not the case! It takes a lot. Which makes sense when you think about it. Everybody's body is different. No one size fits all. This process is way more intense than showing up and picking one. It usually lasts a month-month and a half if all goes well. 
.
After all is said and done, we usually have follow-ups to ensure the new prostethic is fitting correctly and not rubbing the wrong spots on her leg. We also see the surgeon to make sure there is no problem with fit, and ours often checks Evie's hips. 
.
Evie's limb difference does not slow her down. I'm grateful to live in a world where prostethics are available and we are privileged to have access to them. It looks different, but she isn't different. If that makes sense. She can run, jump, dance, climb, and play just like EVERY OTHER 3 year old. #LimbDifferenceAwareness #fatcosyndrome #prostethic #limbdifference #fibulaaplasia #boydamputation

I'm still here for April and #LimbDifferenceAwareness month! 
Some fun facts for you in the caption. 
.
The amputee coalition has a new theme every April for Limb Difference Awareness month. This April, it is "INSPIRE TO ELEVATE." 
.
Most congenital differences are found prior to birth on ultrasounds, but not all. At the ultrasound for Evie, we discovered her hands, but not the absence of her tibia and bowed fibula. I'm still not sure why. 
.
The most common form of limb difference is actually an extra digit in toes or the fingers. According to the Boston Children's Hospital, it is seen in about 1 in every 1000 babies.

What is FATCO? FATCO is Fibular Aplasia- Tibial campomelia- Olygidactly syndrome. It's basically a bunch of Greek for a collection of "findings." 
.
Since Evie's diagnosis, I have learned it is also sometimes called Hecht Scott Syndrome. There is no known causation of this syndrome. 
.
This syndrome looks like shortened legs, missing digits in toes and fingers, and sometimes shortening of arms. Evie has 3 of 4 limbs affected, leaving her right leg unaffected. 
.
This doesn't stop her. It does not slow her down or make her notice anything. Evie is not clueless to her syndrome, but it is not a hindrance. She knows she looks a little different, and she is completely confident in it! I hope that it ALWAYS stays that way. So, I will continue showing, normalizing, and sharing so that if you ever see Evie one day, or someone that looks like her, you don't stare, hush your kids, or ignore her in hopes not to make it weird. I hope you ask her questions, greet her, smile, and go about your day as she will go about hers. She is strong and capable and I hope you see that.
#LimbDifferenceAwareness #limbdifference #fatcosyndrome #Olygidactly #fibulaaplasia #confidentgirl

Hey there!👋 Is it strange to reintroduce yourself? Maybe a little, but I think it's necessary. Many of you have watched me grow up and into a mom and I feel like I'm just coming into myself. 
. 
Becoming a mom turned my world upside down. I held onto my old self for a long time, hoping to bring her back. It was like trying to squeeze back into a cocoon after sprouting wings. A bit cheesy, I know, but it's true.
. 
But in the past year, I've started to fully embraced who I am and what I love. I've accepted that the person I thought I would be is no longer in the cards. And you know what? I'm at peace with that. I stopped putting expectations of others and my old self on me. 
. 
So, let me properly introduce myself. 

.
💙💙Hi, I'm Maddie. I'm a wife to an amazing husband and a mom to three wonderful kids. I absolutely adore motherhood, and I'm proud to say that I'm settling into my mom stereotype. We may be a bit boring, but that's exactly what I hope for. A quiet, fulfilled, and contented life.
. 
In my spare time, I love rearranging my perpetually unfinished house, cheering on my kids in their rec sports, and enjoying family leftovers on Sunday nights. My life is full, and we are genuinely happy.
. 
I hope you'll stick around as I share tips I've learned as a mom of three, lessons I've learned the hard way, and the love that I hope shines through this page. Let's continue to find joy together!😘

It's been 4 years since we last visited this pumpkin patch.🎃 A flood of memories overwhelms me as I reflect on our life when we first moved to NC. We had left behind our large, close-knit families and suddenly found ourselves knowing a whole six people in a new place, new job and new home. We were navigating the growth of becoming a family of four, Evie's FATCO diagnosis and learning about Axel and having Apraxia.
.
Oh, how I wish I could go back and speak to that mama. I would assure her that things get better and life becomes truly amazing. She would be grateful for the path that brought her to NC. I would hug her tight and let her know that both of her kids would surpass their difficulties and it would bring different one, like life always does. I would encourage her to be present and grateful for this stage, as it is fleeting. I know I'll be saying this again in 4 years, but it's always crazy how consumed we get in the problems and forget to be grateful for the good. 
.
Take a moment to slow down, my friends. Embrace the gratitude for the present stage of life because everything changes in the blink of an eye.
